slot.value:
This alarm is generated when a PIU or VM does not start successfully after a number of attempts, either due to hardware or software faults. To avoid further traffic disturbances the PIU or VM is blocked in the following cases: 
*When PM and/or capsule failures on an AP has occured  4 times within 60 minutes.;
*When PM and/or capsule failures on a DP has occured 6 times within 36 minutes.;

The alarm can be triggered for any of the following reasons:
*Heavy disk usage;
*Insufficient disk space on local storage for the system and system_local backup managers;
*Insufficient disk space on /Core for the config backup manager;
*Exceeds maximum backup size;
*Corrupt backup;
*Failure during backup creation;
*Internal error;

The alarm is generated when the disk temperature in the unit is too high. The FsbId parameter indicates the FSB monitoring high temperature and can have the following values:
*FSB-1: the alarm concerns the leftmost FSB;
*FSB-2: the alarm concerns the rightmost FSB;

If the SvMscDnsQueryEnabled parameter is set to false, the alarm is cleared when one of the following conditions is met:
*The peer MSC responds to the GTPv2-C Echo Request message.;
*The peer MSC is deleted by the delete_msc CLI command.;
*The MSC is modified to not support the Sv interface.;
If the SvMscDnsQueryEnabled parameter is set to true, the alarm is cleared when one of the following conditions is met:
*The peer MSC responds to the GTPv2-C Echo Request message.;
*The timer specified by the TResetMscList parameter expires.;
If the SvMscDnsQueryEnabled parameter is changed from true to false, the alarm is cleared for MSCs discovered by DNS query.

The active RP is unavailable because of any of the following reasons:
*SGSN-MME startup;
*Startup after software upgrade;
*RP failover;
*RP switchover;
*Unsuccessful RP failover or switchover;

No action is normally required as the software restarts and recovers from this situation. If the alarm persists, trigger an SGSN-MME restart by running the #node_restart# CLI command with root privileges:;
<userName>@<eqPos> ANCB ~ # sudo node_restart;
#Note: root privileges are gained by using the sudo OS command. Defining sudo rules for a user account allows this user account to use sudo. For information about how to define sudo rules, see #Operator Access Handling#.Note#

This alarm is generated when storm of a specific SCTP event has been detected in a SCTP front-end process or the SS7 O&M entity.
Depending on the alarm cause the following alarm texts are possible:
Event storm of a specific event in the SCTP front-end process:
*Storm of SCTP event <event name> has been detected on EqPos<EqPos>, InstId<number>. The event will be discarded for <number> seconds.;
Event storm in the SS7 O&M entity:
*Storm of SCTP event <event name> has been detected. The event has been deactivated for <number> seconds. <Number> events discarded before deactivation.;

The following are the most likely reasons for this alarm:
*There may be a design error.;
*The databases containing the alarm definitions are not loaded correctly.;
*The databases containing the alarm definitions were not properly generated.;

The following maintenance activities need to be initiated to resolve the communication failure if the alarm is persistent: 
*Check the configured server address and port, using the get_mdtm_tce_server or the get_mdtm_tce_ipv6server CLI command.;
*Check the IP connection towards the external server. If it does not work properly, repair the connection.;
*Check if the external server is working as expected. If not, perform required operations such as restarting applications on the external server.;

The standby RP is unavailable due to any of the following reasons:
*Node start-up;
*Start-up after software upgrade;
*RP failover;
*RP switchover;
*Unsuccessful RP failover or switchover;
*Only one NCB is available, that is, one of the NCB is blocked or removed for maintenance;

This alarm is cleared in two situations:
When the fault ratio of ok to total remote endpoints has risen to 5 percentage points greater than the GbIpNseAvailabilityDecreasedThreshold percent value for the NSEI. This can occur when any of the following actions has been performed successfully: 
*The BSS has initiated a new dynamic configuration procedure.; 
*The BSS has initiated an SNS Changeweight procedure for a remote endpoint marked as suspect.; 
*The BSS has initiated an SNS Delete procedure for a remote endpoint marked as suspect.; 
*The BSS has initiated an SNS Add procedure for a remote endpoints marked as suspect.; 
*The BSS has initiated an SNS Add procedure for a previous unknown remote endpoint.;
When all remote endpoints are marked as suspect and the alarm #gbipNseUnavailable# has been generated for this NSEI.

This alarm is generated when storm of a specific SS7 event has been detected in a SS7 front-end process, SS7 back-end process or the SS7 O&M entity.
Depending on the alarm cause the following alarm texts are possible:
Event storm of a specific event in the SS7 front-end process:
*Storm of SS7 event <event name> has been detected on EqPos <EqPos>, InstId<number>. The event will be discarded for <number> seconds.;
Event storm of a specific event in the SS7 back-end process:
*Storm of SS7 event <event name> has been detected. The event will be discarded for <number> seconds.;
Event storm in the SS7 O&M entity:
*Storm of SS7 event <event name> has been detected. The event has been deactivated for <number> seconds. <Number> events discarded before deactivation.;

This alarm is generated if the CPU has discovered a single bad path to another CPU over the Ethernet backplane.

*For MkVIII, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and load sharing for communication between the CPUs. One of the redundant Ethernet paths connects the CPUs through the SCXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and one redundant path is connected through the SCXB on the right-hand side of the magazine. One of the redundant Ethernet paths connects the CPUs through the CMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and one redundant path is connected through the CMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.;
*For MkX, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and load sharing for communication between the CPUs. Two redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet paths connect the CPUs through the SMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant paths are connected through the SMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.;
The purpose of the redundant Ethernet alarm is to detect fault situations in the redundant Ethernet. The single fault alarm arises when a single bad path occurs in one of the redundant Ethernet networks. The redundant networks raise alarms independent of each other and every PIU in the network sends redundant Ethernet alarms independent of each other. For more information, see #Resilience#.;

Alarm Description Definitions:
#Term: Network path Term##Def: A network path is the full-duplex communication channel between two CPUs over the Ethernet backplane. Def#

#Term: Bad path Term##Def: A bad path is when a network path fails. Note that the redundant Ethernet takes care of this problem and uses the other redundant network instead, but an alarm is sent, nonetheless. Def#

If there are one multiple fault and one, or many single fault alarms, this is probably due to a faulty network interface on the PIU that reports the multiple fault alarm, or on the Ethernet switching PIU in between. The single fault alarms indicate a bad path to the PIU that has the multiple fault alarm. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Block the PIU with the faulty network interface by using the #block_eq# CLI command and deblock it again by using the #deblock_eq# CLI command.;
**Restart the malfunctioning PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an FSB# or #Replacing a GEP#.;
**Restart the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an SCXB#, #Replacing a CMXB#, or #Replacing an SMXB#.;

Verify the network connectivity to assure that IP routing is possible between all IP endpoints of the SGSN and the BSS (full-mesh connectivity).;

Involving the BSS O&M staff, verify that all IP endpoints configured in the BSS are locally available.;

Initiate in the BSS a new SNS SIZE procedure for the Gb interface.;

Additional Information could be derived if the event #gbipNseNSStatusReceived# is generated for the same NSEI.

Take the following actions:
**Define this specific MCC and MNC, by using the #create_plmn# CLI command.;
**Start the BSSGP initialization by resetting all signaling BVCs, by using the #action_gb_ip_nse_reset_signaling_bvc# CLI command.;

Take the following actions:
**Define an MCC and an MNC, by using the #create_plmn# CLI command.;
**In case the PLMN is associated with GPRS traffic start the BSSGP initialization by resetting all signaling BVCs, by using the #action_gb_ip_nse_reset_signaling_bvc# CLI command.;

If this alarm is not automatically cleared, perform the following actions on the MME:
*Use the show_sgs_lite_sds_gw_connection CLI command to check the TCP connections and the corresponding status.;
*Reconfigure the MinimumTcpConnections parameter to a lower value if the current value is too high.;

This alarm is generated when storm of SCTP alarms or a specific SCTP alarm has been detected in a SCTP front-end process or the SS7 O&M entity.
Depending on the alarm cause the following alarm texts are possible:
Alarm storm of a specific alarm in the SCTP front-end process:
*Storm of SCTP alarm <alarm name> has been detected on EqPos<EqPos>, InstId<number>. The alarm will be discarded for <number> seconds.;
Alarm storm of a specific clear alarm in the SCTP front-end process:
*Storm of SCTP alarm <alarm name> (clear) has been detected on EqPos<EqPos>, InstId<number>. The alarm has been cleared and will be discarded for <number> seconds.;
Alarm storm in the SCTP front-end process:
*Storm of SCTP alarms has been detected on EqPos<EqPos>, InstId<number>. Some SCTP alarms will be discarded.;
Alarm storm in the SS7 O&M entity:
*Storm of SCTP alarm <alarm name> has been detected. The alarm has been cleared and deactivated for <number> seconds. <Number> alarms discarded before deactivation.;

Depending on the alarm cause the following alarm texts are possible.
If the association goes down:
*SCTP communication for M3UA association with RemoteSpId <number> and LocalSpId <number> on SctpEndPointNo <number> was lost. SCTP reason is <number>. Origin is <Local user|Remote peer>.;
If the association establishment is unsuccessful (SCTP_COMMLOST_ind received while waiting for the association establishment):
*Unable to establish M3UA association with RemoteSpId <number> and LocalSpId <number> on SctpEndPointNo <number>. Cause for establish failure is 1. SCTP reason is <number>. Origin is <Local user|Remote peer>.;
If the association establishment is unsuccessful (M3UA TimerTassoc expiration while waiting for the association establishment):
*Unable to establish the M3UA association with RemoteSpId <number> and LocalSpId <number> on SctpEndPointNo <number>. Cause for establish failure is 2. Origin is <Local user|Remote peer>.;
If the association establishment is unsuccessful (SCTP_ASSOCIATE_conf returned error code. Association configuration error):
*Unable to establish the M3UA association with RemoteSpId <number> and LocalSpId <number> on SctpEndPointNo <number>. Cause for establishing failure is 3. SCTP return code is <number>. Origin is <Local user|Remote peer>.;

Depending on alarm cause, which is stated in the alarm text, do as follows:
*If the M3UA association could not be established, check the remote IP configuration. For example, check IP addresses, IP routing, and SCTP endpoints in the remote node as well as in routers and other network elements between the SGSN-MME and the remote node.;
*If the M3UA association went down, the association is restarted by the M3UA. This is a timer-controlled process that normally makes the association come back into service.;

If the association does not come back into service, check the physical connections and hardware. For example, check for broken cables, or oxidized or loose connections.
*If the M3UA association is unavailable due to manual operations, perform a manual start of the M3UA association.;
For more information regarding start of M3UA local application server, and its corresponding M3UA associations, see SS7 - M3UA Local AS (CLI).
Further information can be available in the SS7 log file, ss7trace.log.

This alarm is generated if the CPU has discovered more than one bad path from the CPU to other CPUs over the Ethernet backplane.

*For MkVIII, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and loadsharing for communication between the CPUs. One of the redundant (1GE) Ethernet paths connects the CPUs via the SCXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant path is connected through the SCXB on the right-hand side of the magazine. One of the redundant (10GE) Ethernet paths connects the CPUs through the CMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant path is connected through the CMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.; 
*For MkX, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and load sharing for communication between the CPUs. Two redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet paths connect the CPUs through the SMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant paths are connected through the SMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.;
 The purpose of the redundant Ethernet alarm is to detect fault situations in the redundant Ethernet. The multiple fault alarm arises when more than one bad paths occur in one of the redundant Ethernet networks. The redundant networks raise alarms independent of each other and every PIU in the network sends redundant Ethernet alarms independent of each other. For more information, see #Resilience#.;

Alarm Description Definitions:

#Term: Network path Term##Def: A network path is the full-duplex communication channel between two CPUs over the Ethernet backplane. Def#
#Term: Bad path Term##Def: A bad path is when a network path fails. Note that the redundant Ethernet takes care of this problem and uses the other redundant network instead, but an alarm is sent, nonetheless. Def#

Analyze the fault situation for one network at a time and see if the situation matches any of the three fault situations below.

If all PIUs in the magazines raise the multiple fault alarm to all PIUs in another magazine, this is likely due to a faulty or removed cable between the magazines. There can also be some lost SCXBs and CMXBs or SMXBs on the left-hand side of the magazines. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Verify that the cables between the left SCXBs CMXBs or SMXBs in the magazines are properly connected.;
**Replace the cable.; 

If all PIUs in the SGSN-MME raise the multiple fault alarm to other PIUs, this is likely due to that the Ethernet switching functionality has stopped working in one SCXB, CMXB, or SMXB. The malfunctioning PIU is located on the left-hand side. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Restart the malfunctioning PIU by using the #restart_eqm_element# CLI command.;
**Power off the malfunctioning PIU and then power it on again by following the instructions in #Replacing an SCXB#, #Replacing a CMXB#, or #Replacing an SMXB#. Insert the same PIU back into the magazine during replacement.;
**Replace the malfunctioning PIU.;

If there are one multiple fault and one, or many single fault alarms, this is probably due to a faulty network interface on the PIU that reports the multiple fault alarm, or on the Ethernet switching PIU in between. The single fault alarms indicate a bad path to the PIU that has the multiple fault alarm. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Block the PIU with the faulty network interface by using the #block_eq# CLI command and deblock it again by using the #deblock_eq# CLI command.;
**Restart the malfunctioning PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an FSB# or #Replacing a GEP#.;
**Restart the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an SCXB#, #Replacing a CMXB#, or #Replacing an SMXB#.;

The alarm will be cleared when:
*The TA RAT type carried in a new S1 Setup Request or eNB Configuration Update message is the same as the RAT type configured for this TA.;
*After 24 hours if no further S1 Setup Request or eNB Configuration Update message is received from this eNodeB.;

The alarm can be caused by the following:
*The PLMN identity is not valid for the AMF;
*The PLMN identity is not configured in the AMF;
*Faulty DNS configuration, which has caused the gNodeB to connect to the wrong AMF;
#Note:If more than one PLMN identity is received, the alarm will only be generated if none of the received identities are valid for the AMF.Note#
For information regarding the current network configuration, see the appropriate network planning documentation.

Depending on the suspected cause of the alarm, do the following:
The PLMN identity is not valid for the AMF:
*Check the PLMN identity in the gNodeB. For more information, see the corresponding documentation for the gNodeB.;
*If the PLMN identity differs between the AMF and the gNodeB, change it in the gNodeB.;
The PLMN identity is not configured in the AMF:
*Check if the PLMN identity is configured in the AMF, using the #list_plmn# CLI command.;
*If the PLMN identity is missing, configure it using the #create_plmn# CLI command.;
The gNodeB is connected to the wrong AMF:
*Check the DNS configuration.;
*If the DNS configuration is incorrect, reconfigure it so that the gNodeB does not connect to this AMF anymore.;
All nwcGnodeBPlmnMismatch alarms that are older than 24 hours, will be cleared. To force the clearing of alarms before the 24 hours have elapsed, use the clear_alarms CLI command.
For more information regarding handling of disconnected gNodeBs, see #N2 Interface Description#.

The alarm will be cleared:
*When a new NG Setup Request that includes a PLMN Identity that is configured in the AMF is received from the gNodeB;
*After 24 hours if no further NG Setup Request is received from this gNodeB;

The alarm is cleared in the following cases:
*The Blacklist GGSN feature is turned off.;
*The blacklist timer for the GGSN expires. The initial value of the timer is specified by the ResetBlacklistEchoFrequency parameter, which is set to 24 hours by default.;
*The SGSN receives an answer to a Blacklist Echo Request message from the GGSN.;

