This alarm is generated when an external clock source fails. This indicates a cable problem or a remote peer down.
When the primary clock source is lost:
*Primary clock source PCM trunk A is lost on EqPos <EqPos>, failover to stand-by clock source PCM trunk C.;
When both the primary and the stand-by clock sources are lost:
*Primary clock source PCM trunk A and stand-by clock source PCM trunk C are lost on EqPos <EqPos>, failover to local clock.;
When the stand-by clock source is lost:
*Stand-by clock source PCM trunk C is lost on EqPos <EqPos>.;
#Note:This alarm is only applicable for the ITU-T standard. On MkVIII hardware configurations, the alarm is only applicable for time slot-based narrowband, not HSL.Note#

If it takes more than one hour before the Erlang clock is synchronized, do the following: 
*For physical SGSN-MME, trigger a manual SGSN-MME restart to synchronize the clocks. Huge time gaps between PIUs can cause disturbances and escalations.;
*For virtual SGSN-MME, first ensure that the compute hosts have their time synchronized correctly. If the compute host has accurate and synchronized time, trigger a manual SGSN-MME restart to synchronize the clocks. Huge time gaps between VMs can cause disturbances and escalations.;
To restart the SGSN-MME, run #node_restart# with root privileges:; <userName>@<eqPos> ANCB ~ # sudo node_restart; #Note: root privileges are gained by using the sudo OS command. Defining sudo rules for a user account allows this user account to use sudo. For information about how to define sudo rules, see #Operator Access Handling#.Note#

This alarm is generated if the backplane Ethernet link of the magazine switch hosted on the SCXB, CMXB, or SMXB fails to reach  full capacity during auto-negotiation.

The port number (3-6) displayed in the alarm text indicates which magazine and which PIU is causing the reduced link capacity:

*Port 3 - 1GbE left hand side magazine switch, either SCXB or SMXB;
*Port 4 - 1GbE right hand side magazine switch, either SCXB or SMXB;
*Port 5 - 10GbE left hand side magazine switch, either CMXB or SMXB;
*Port 6 - 10GbE right hand side magazine switch, either CMXB or SMXB;

This alarm is generated when a cell is sent from the BSC containing a routing area which has already been defined as a cooperating routing area in the SGSN.  
This alarm can occur, for example: 
*During network reconfigurations, such as migration to SGSN Pool.;
*When moving a BSC to a new SGSN, and the SGSN that the BSC was previously connected to is defined as a cooperating SGSN in the new SGSN.;

This alarm is generated when storm of SS7 alarms or a specific SS7 alarm has been detected in a SS7 front-end process, SS7 back-end process or the SS7 O&M entity.
