One of the SS7 devices is not available for SS7 signaling.;
This alarm is generated in one of the following situations:
*Control system restarts (including small restart, large restart, initial start up, software upgrade, software update, and patching).;
*During the restart of an SS7 device.;
*A blocked PIU or VM executing SS7 functionality.;

The alarm generates one of the following texts:
*SS7 PIU or VM <EqId> is blocked;
*The SS7 devices on <EqId> is not available for SS7 signaling;
*Failed to bind the following subsystem on <EqId>: SSN <SSN>: <Reason>, SSN <SSN>: <Reason>;

This alarm is generated when an SS7 device becomes unavailable for SS7 signaling.
The reasons for this may be as follows:
*SS7 configuration problem.;
*Internal software error or hardware failure.;
*A manually or automatically blocked PIU or VM.;

Allow a few minutes for the alarm to clear automatically. If the alarm remains, take the following actions:
*Check for hardware failures.;
*Unblock the blocked PIU or VM, by using the #deblock_eq# CLI command.;
*Contact Ericsson support.;

Use one or both of the following to stop the alarm:
*Increase the log file's value for Max. File Age by using the #set_chs_config# CLI command. This ensures that the log files remain in the target directory for a longer period of time.;
Reduce the size of the delivered log files by using a combination of the following:
*Reduce the log file size in the Max. File Size by using the #set_log_config# CLI command.;*Reduce the value in the Push Size (%) field  by using the #set_chs_config# CLI command.;*Check the functioning of the Billing system or the links to it.;*Check for alarms: chsBGw.;

This alarm is raised when the installed SFP/SFP+ transceiver type cannot be identified. This can be because of the following reasons:
*The installed SFP/SFP+ transceiver is not supported.;
*The SFP/SFP+ transceiver identification data cannot be read because of hardware fault.;

