The alarm text details shown in the alarm text can indicate if the alarm is caused by a disk problem or by frequent application restarts.

This alarm is generated if the CPU has discovered more than one bad paths from the CPU to other CPUs over the Ethernet backplane.

*For MkVIII, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and load sharing for communication between the CPUs. One of the redundant (1GE) Ethernet paths connects the CPUs through the SCXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant path is connected through the SCXB on the right-hand side of the magazine. One of the redundant (10GE) Ethernet paths connects the CPUs through the CMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant path is connected through the CMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.; 
*For MkX, each CPU has 2+2 redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet networks that are used for redundancy and load sharing for communication between the CPUs. Two redundant (1GE and 10GE) Ethernet paths connect the CPUs through the SMXB on the left-hand side of the magazine, and the other redundant paths are connected through the SMXB on the right-hand side of the magazine.;
The purpose of the redundant Ethernet alarm is to detect fault situations in the redundant Ethernet. The multiple fault alarm arises when more than one bad paths occur in one of the redundant Ethernet networks. The redundant networks raise alarms independent of each other and every PIU in the network sends redundant Ethernet alarms independent of each other. For more information, see #Resilience#.;

Alarm Description Definitions:

#Term: Network path Term##Def: A network path is the full-duplex communication channel between two CPUs over the Ethernet backplane. Def#
#Term: Bad path Term##Def: A bad path is when a network path fails. Note that the redundant Ethernet takes care of this problem and uses the other redundant network instead, but an alarm is sent, nonetheless. Def#

Analyze the fault situation for one network at a time and see if the situation matches any of the three fault situations below.

If all PIUs in the magazines raise the multiple fault alarm to all PIUs in another magazine, this is likely due to a faulty or removed cable between the magazines. There can also be some lost SCXBs and CMXBs or SMXBs on the right-hand side of the magazines. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Verify that the cables between the right SCXBs CMXBs or SMXBs in the magazines are properly connected.;
**Replace the cables.; 

If all PIUs in the SGSN-MME raise the multiple fault alarm to other PIUs, this is likely due to that the Ethernet switching functionality has stopped working in one SCXB, CMXB, or SMXB. The malfunctioning PIU is located on the right-hand side. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Restart the malfunctioning PIU by using the #restart_eqm_element# CLI command.;
**Power off the malfunctioning PIU and then power it on again by following the instructions in #Replacing an SCXB#, #Replacing a CMXB#, or #Replacing an SMXB#. Insert the same PIU back into the magazine during replacement.;
**Replace the malfunctioning PIU.;

If there are one multiple fault and one, or many single fault alarms, this is probably due to a faulty network interface on the PIU that reports the multiple fault alarm, or on the Ethernet switching PIU in between. The single fault alarms indicate a bad path to the PIU that has the multiple fault alarm. Take the following steps and check if the alarms are cleared by using the #list_alarms# CLI command after each step:

**Block the PIU with the faulty network interface by using the #block_eq# CLI command and deblock it again by using the #deblock_eq# CLI command.;
**Restart the malfunctioning PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an FSB# or #Replacing a GEP#.;
**Restart the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU using the CLI command restart_eqm_element -eqm { x y } -cold.;
**Replace the malfunctioning Ethernet switching PIU by following the instructions in #Replacing an SCXB#, #Replacing a CMXB#, or #Replacing an SMXB#.;

Check if clock reference and clock sources are correct, using the get_ss7_mtpl2 CLI command. The following clock configurations should be checked:
*Clock reference;
The clock reference in the local node should be the logical opposite to the corresponding parameter value in the remote node. For example, if the clock reference is set to external clocking in the local node, it should be set to local clocking in the remote node.;
*External clock source;
The same external clock source should be used in both the local node and the remote node.;
*Standby clock source;
The same standby clock source should be used in both the local node and the remote node.

If required, change the clock configurations using the modify_ss7_mtpl2 CLI command.

For more information regarding the CLI commands, see SS7 - MTP-L2 Base Parameter (CLI) and the corresponding documentation for the remote node.

This alarm is generated if a disk fault is detected on a FSB. Only the FSB has storage media and the PIU will try to repair itself. The fault can be detected either by the disk itself, or by the operating system. The FsbId parameter indicates the faulty FSB and can have the following values:
*FSB-1: the alarm concerns the leftmost FSB;
*FSB-2: the alarm concerns the rightmost FSB;

For Virtual: 
This alarm indicates the existence of some problems with access to the disk on the faulty FSB. This problem can be caused by connectivity problems, read or write errors in the Cloud HW.

The export can fail for any of the following reasons:
*The value of the AutoExportUri parameter is invalid.;
*The value of the AutoExportPassword parameter is invalid.;
*The SGSN-MME has failed to connect to the remote SFTP server.;
*Object missing. The local backup has been deleted and the node has been restarted.;

The alarm is cleared in the following cases:
*The scheduled backup is successfully exported.;
*The scheduled backup event is deleted.;
*The automatic export of backups is disabled for the relevant backup scheduler.;
*The relevant backup scheduler is disabled.;

This alarm is generated when no secondary FSB is available. This means that no spare FSB is currently available or the FSB disk is not mirrored yet. The fault can occur:
*During initial installation;
*During a switch of the primary FSB because of a controlled switchover during SW upgrades;
*Because of HW or SW faults;
Switching the primary FSB causes re-mirroring of the storage media.
#Note: If the FSBs synchronize in less than the predefined time interval during FSB restart, the alarm is not raised. The time intervals are as follows:Note#
*On physical SGSN-MME, 5 minutes;
*On virtual SGSN-MME, 1 minute;
#Note: fsbNoDiskRedundacy is reported on system level, thus the position of the unavailable FSB is indicated as FSB-0.Note#

The SGSN-MME will try to re-mirror the storage media, and the alarm should clear itself when the mirroring is done. The synchronization can take up to several hours and is dependent on the synchronization rate and actual bandwidth.
If the alarm is not automatically cleared within 6 hours, do the following:
*On physical SGSN-MME, replace the secondary FSB PIU. See #Replacing an FSB#.;
*On virtual SGSN-MME, migrate the secondary VM to another host. See the cloud system documentation.;

An AP take over is triggered. The consequences of this event are as follows:
*Stable subscribers on the restarting AP survive the restart.;
*Unstable subscribers will be detached with a reattach indication if the state is Attached or Active. In Idle state no detach is sent. Unstable subscribers are, for instance, subscribers in the middle of a control signaling sequence.;

